Subject: [bioinfo] two Post-Doctoral Research Positions in computational structural biology / structural bioinformatics (INRIA Grenoble)

Two post-doctoral research positions are open in the framework of the PEPSI=
 (Polynomial Expansions of Protein Structures and Interactions) ANR project=
 (http://pepsi.gforge.inria.fr) at NANO-D group of INRIA Grenoble (http://n=
ano-d.inrialpes.fr).

The goal of the first position is to develop an exhaustive-search FFT-based=
 method that incorporates a very detailed knowledge-based interaction poten=
tial. This will combine the speed of FFT-accelerated techniques (which are,=
 however, rather inaccurate) with the precision of state-of-the-art scoring=
 functions (which are too slow otherwise). This work will be grounded on th=
e spherical polar Fourier (SPF) correlation FFT docking algorithm developed=
 by our collaborators (Ritchie and Kemp 2000), which operates on potentials=
 expressed in a basis of orthogonal functions. Later, we will express the k=
nowledge-base potential in the Cartesian basis set and utilize a polar/Cart=
esian FFT algorithm.

The second position is for the development of algorithms for annotating and=
 fitting of electron density maps. Medium resolution cryoEM electron densit=
y maps pose a challenge: at sub-nanometer resolution, =CE=B1-helices become=
 resolvable, and as the resolution improves further, =CE=B2-sheets become d=
iscernible, eventually showing strand separation. In this intermediate (~5-=
10 =C3=85) resolution range, tools for automatic identification and localiz=
ation of secondary structure elements become quite valuable. The first task=
 will be to use supervised learning and exhaustive search techniques to aut=
omatically identify regions inside the map that belong to different structu=
ral traits, =CE=B1-helices or =CE=B2-sheets. Grounded on our recently devel=
oped exhaustive=E2=80=93search FFT-based algorithms for fitting a structure=
 into a density map, the second task deals with symmetry information in the=
 formulation of the fitting problem.=20

Desired profile:
We are looking for creative, passionate and hard-working individuals with e=
xceptional talent for computer science and mathematics. Excellent oral, wri=
tten and interpersonal communication skills are essential (working language=
 will be English =E2=80=93 knowledge of French is not necessary, but a plus=
).

